@jon-wei I revert the last commit since it would change the expected behavior and cause the CI failures. 
> Using the iterator would avoid the ISE, but I think it's still possible to persist a Sink that was already abandoned (i.e., abandonSegment could remove a Sink after that Sink is returned by iterator.next() in persistAll)).

I think there is no need to concern this. `abandonSegment` is called in `clear` , `close` and `drop` : 
1. In `clear`, here is the code, it will await the dropping.

```java
        // Drop everything.
        final List<ListenableFuture<?>> futures = Lists.newArrayList();
        for (Map.Entry<SegmentIdentifier, Sink> entry : sinks.entrySet()) {
          futures.add(abandonSegment(entry.getKey(), entry.getValue(), true));
        }

        // Await dropping.
        Futures.allAsList(futures).get();
```
  2. In `close`, it will also await the dropping and shutdown the `persistExecutor`.
  3. In `drop`, it means the handoff operation have been finished, which means the the `hydrant`s 
   have been already swapped and will be ignored to persist.

